[
    {
        "content": "<p>For any object <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span></span></span></span> in a topos, there is a canonical singleton map <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>X</mi><mo>→</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Ω</mi><mi>X</mi></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">X \\to \\Omega^X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8413309999999999em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord\">Ω</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.8413309999999999em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> which is the analogue of the mapping of elements to their singleton subsets in the category of sets. Does this map have a universal property that doesn't rely on knowing  <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span></span></span></span> beforehand?<br>\nAnother way of asking this is as follows: suppose I have an object <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>Y</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">Y</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.22222em;\">Y</span></span></span></span>; is there a way to reconstruct an <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span></span></span></span> such that <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>Y</mi><mo>=</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Ω</mi><mi>X</mi></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">Y = \\Omega^X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.22222em;\">Y</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">=</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8413309999999999em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord\">Ω</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.8413309999999999em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span>, if such an <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span></span></span></span> exists?</p>",
        "id": 244952217,
        "sender_full_name": "Morgan Rogers (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1625500857
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>The singleton mapping is a monomorphism (see Corollary A2.2.3 in the <em>Elephant</em>), so the above amounts to identifying what the properties of this \"special subobject\" should be.</p>",
        "id": 244953322,
        "sender_full_name": "Morgan Rogers (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1625501641
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>If it helps, as a starting point, I'm happy to assume that we have some ordering structure on <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>Y</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">Y</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.22222em;\">Y</span></span></span></span> here.</p>",
        "id": 244953729,
        "sender_full_name": "Morgan Rogers (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1625501940
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I'm not sure about the general singleton map, but if <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span></span></span></span> is a poset, then the object of order preserving maps from <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mi>X</mi><mtext>op</mtext></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">X^\\text{op}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.664392em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord text mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">op</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> to <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Ω</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\Omega</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">Ω</span></span></span></span> is the free cocompletion of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span></span></span></span>.</p>",
        "id": 244957410,
        "sender_full_name": "Fawzi Hreiki",
        "timestamp": 1625504580
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>But this is just the Yoneda lemma for posets (except internalised to the topos)</p>",
        "id": 244957458,
        "sender_full_name": "Fawzi Hreiki",
        "timestamp": 1625504626
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Given an object <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>Y</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">Y</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.22222em;\">Y</span></span></span></span>, the question of whether or not you can find an <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span></span></span></span> such that <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>Y</mi><mo>=</mo><mi mathvariant=\"script\">P</mi><mi>X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">Y = \\mathcal{P}X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.22222em;\">Y</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">=</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.08222em;\">P</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span></span></span></span> seems in general intractable.</p>",
        "id": 244957831,
        "sender_full_name": "Fawzi Hreiki",
        "timestamp": 1625504871
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I recall reading somewhere that there are models of ZFC where the power set operation is not injective.</p>",
        "id": 244958079,
        "sender_full_name": "Fawzi Hreiki",
        "timestamp": 1625505039
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"341237\">Fawzi Hreiki</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/230087-theory.3A-topos.20theory/topic/singleton.20morphism/near/244957831\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Given an object <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>Y</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">Y</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.22222em;\">Y</span></span></span></span>, the question of whether or not you can find an <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span></span></span></span> such that <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>Y</mi><mo>=</mo><mi mathvariant=\"script\">P</mi><mi>X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">Y = \\mathcal{P}X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.22222em;\">Y</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">=</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.08222em;\">P</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span></span></span></span> seems in general intractable.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>If this is the internal Yoneda lemma, might it be possible to use an (internal version of the) characterisation of presheaf categories <a href=\"https://ncatlab.org/nlab/show/atomic+category#relation_to_presheaf_toposes\">as cocomplete atomic categories</a> to answer this question?</p>",
        "id": 244958437,
        "sender_full_name": "Nathanael Arkor",
        "timestamp": 1625505329
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I think you need to consider structured objects and structure preserving maps for that to work (for some kind of structure, e.g. category objects).</p>",
        "id": 244961437,
        "sender_full_name": "Fawzi Hreiki",
        "timestamp": 1625507920
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"276092\">Nathanael Arkor</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/230087-theory.3A-topos.20theory/topic/singleton.20morphism/near/244958437\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"341237\">Fawzi Hreiki</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/230087-theory.3A-topos.20theory/topic/singleton.20morphism/near/244957831\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Given an object <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>Y</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">Y</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.22222em;\">Y</span></span></span></span>, the question of whether or not you can find an <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span></span></span></span> such that <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>Y</mi><mo>=</mo><mi mathvariant=\"script\">P</mi><mi>X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">Y = \\mathcal{P}X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.22222em;\">Y</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">=</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.08222em;\">P</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span></span></span></span> seems in general intractable.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>If this is the internal Yoneda lemma, might it be possible to use an (internal version of the) characterisation of presheaf categories <a href=\"https://ncatlab.org/nlab/show/atomic+category#relation_to_presheaf_toposes\">as cocomplete atomic categories</a> to answer this question?</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>This sounds like an outdated use of the term \"atom\" for \"tiny object\".<br>\nThat concept seems promising, at least initially: in Set, if we take <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Ω</mi><mi>X</mi></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\Omega^X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8413309999999999em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord\">Ω</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.8413309999999999em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> as a distributive lattice, we can identify <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span></span></span></span> with the union of the atoms in that lattice. But I don't immediately see how to abstract this: I would need a notion of \"generalized atom\". One idea would be to make it representable: attempt to construct the subpresheaf of the representable <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">o</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mo>−</mo><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Ω</mi><mi>X</mi></msup><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathrm{Hom}(-,\\Omega^X)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1.0913309999999998em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathrm\">Hom</span></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord\">−</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.16666666666666666em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord\">Ω</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.8413309999999999em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span> which sends <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>Z</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">Z</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">Z</span></span></span></span> to the union of the atoms in the lattice <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">o</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>Z</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Ω</mi><mi>X</mi></msup><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathrm{Hom}(Z,\\Omega^X)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1.0913309999999998em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathrm\">Hom</span></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">Z</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.16666666666666666em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord\">Ω</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.8413309999999999em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span>; is this functorial?</p>",
        "id": 244973889,
        "sender_full_name": "Morgan Rogers (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1625518801
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>We would need to include the fact that <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Ω</mi><mi>X</mi></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\Omega^X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8413309999999999em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord\">Ω</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.8413309999999999em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> is a complete lattice for this to work, I suppose, which is not ideal for my intended application of this characterization.<br>\n<span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"341237\">Fawzi Hreiki</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/230087-theory.3A-topos.20theory/topic/singleton.20morphism/near/244961437\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>I think you need to consider structured objects and structure preserving maps for that to work (for some kind of structure, e.g. category objects).</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>A sufficiently flexible Stone-type duality would probably do, even a posetal one. I'll look into that.</p>",
        "id": 244974346,
        "sender_full_name": "Morgan Rogers (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1625519220
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Do you only care about characterising when an object is a power object or also about extracting the (or some) object which it is a power object of?</p>",
        "id": 244978835,
        "sender_full_name": "Fawzi Hreiki",
        "timestamp": 1625524169
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>The characterisation question is much easier than the extraction one. For example, in <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mtext>Set</mtext></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\text{Set}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord text\"><span class=\"mord\">Set</span></span></span></span></span>, complete atomic Boolean algebras are precisely the power sets.</p>",
        "id": 244978916,
        "sender_full_name": "Fawzi Hreiki",
        "timestamp": 1625524253
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"341237\">Fawzi Hreiki</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/230087-theory.3A-topos.20theory/topic/singleton.20morphism/near/244978916\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>The characterisation question is much easier than the extraction one. For example, in <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mtext>Set</mtext></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\text{Set}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord text\"><span class=\"mord\">Set</span></span></span></span></span>, complete atomic Boolean algebras are precisely the power sets.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Wait, are you claiming that isn't constructive? You can just take the set of atoms in a CABA to recover a set isomorphic to the one being exponentiated. My problem is working out what the equivalent process should be in a not-necessarily-Boolean setting.</p>",
        "id": 244998395,
        "sender_full_name": "Morgan Rogers (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1625551198
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>The problem seems to be that, constructively, <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"script\">P</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>X</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathcal{P}(X)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.08222em;\">P</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span> does not have to be a boolean algebra.</p>\n<p>Some background is given on <a href=\"https://ncatlab.org/nlab/show/complete+Boolean+algebra\">this nLab page</a>. On this page, CABA is not used as an abbreviation of complete atomic boolean algebra, but is defined to be something else.</p>",
        "id": 245013174,
        "sender_full_name": "Jens Hemelaer",
        "timestamp": 1625562771
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Sometimes <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span></span></span></span> is called the \"object of points\" of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Ω</mi><mi>X</mi></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\Omega^X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8413309999999999em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord\">Ω</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.8413309999999999em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span>. This seems to suggest that <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span></span></span></span> is the subobject of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Ω</mi><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Ω</mi><mi>X</mi></msup><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\Omega^{(\\Omega^X)}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1.006365em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord\">Ω</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:1.006365em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mopen mtight\">(</span><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">Ω</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.9190928571428572em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.931em;margin-right:0.07142857142857144em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.5em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size3 size1 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mclose mtight\">)</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> consisting of the \"internal frame morphisms\". But I would have to think about what this means concretely.</p>",
        "id": 245013328,
        "sender_full_name": "Jens Hemelaer",
        "timestamp": 1625562867
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"282722\">Jens Hemelaer</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/230087-theory.3A-topos.20theory/topic/singleton.20morphism/near/245013174\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Some background is given on <a href=\"https://ncatlab.org/nlab/show/complete+Boolean+algebra\">this nLab page</a>. On this page, CABA is not used as an abbreviation of complete atomic boolean algebra, but is defined to be something else.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Since I'm in the middle of arguing about naming conventions elsewhere, I want to put out there that this is a terrible naming convention, which fortunately does not seem to have become standard.</p>",
        "id": 245014047,
        "sender_full_name": "Morgan Rogers (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1625563340
    },
    {
        "content": "<blockquote>\n<p>For any object <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span></span></span></span> in a topos, there is a canonical singleton map <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>X</mi><mo>→</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Ω</mi><mi>X</mi></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">X \\to \\Omega^X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8413309999999999em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord\">Ω</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.8413309999999999em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> which is the analogue of the mapping of elements to their singleton subsets in the category of sets. Does this map have a universal property that doesn't rely on knowing  <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span></span></span></span> beforehand?<br>\nAnother way of asking this is as follows: suppose I have an object <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>Y</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">Y</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.22222em;\">Y</span></span></span></span>; is there a way to reconstruct an <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span></span></span></span> such that <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>Y</mi><mo>=</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Ω</mi><mi>X</mi></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">Y = \\Omega^X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.22222em;\">Y</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">=</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8413309999999999em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord\">Ω</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.8413309999999999em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span>, if such an <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span></span></span></span> exists?</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>That map is the transpose of the equality predicate on <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span></span></span></span>. Maybe equality is more readily characterized? I used to know this stuff <span aria-label=\"sweat smile\" class=\"emoji emoji-1f605\" role=\"img\" title=\"sweat smile\">:sweat_smile:</span></p>",
        "id": 245014656,
        "sender_full_name": "Matteo Capucci (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1625563711
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Mmh but I probably misunderstood your question</p>",
        "id": 245014679,
        "sender_full_name": "Matteo Capucci (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1625563731
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>You want to characterize those maps <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>A</mi><mo>→</mo><mi>B</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">A \\to B</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05017em;\">B</span></span></span></span> which happen to be isomorphic to the singleton mono?</p>",
        "id": 245014721,
        "sender_full_name": "Matteo Capucci (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1625563763
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>No. The question is (as I understand it) given some (possibly structured) object in a topos, can we know when it’s a power object?</p>",
        "id": 245016559,
        "sender_full_name": "Fawzi Hreiki",
        "timestamp": 1625564988
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>The same way we can pick out power set posets as the complete atomic Boolean algebras and we can pick out presheaf categories as the cocomplete atomic categories.</p>",
        "id": 245016685,
        "sender_full_name": "Fawzi Hreiki",
        "timestamp": 1625565064
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>If we are allowed to remember the order structure isn't this trivial? There also isn't any problem with doing it constructively. If Y is a poset, then it is isomorphic to the powerset of a set X if and only if Y is a frame corresponding to a discrete locale and X is isomorphic to its set of points. We just need an intrinsic definition of when a locale is discrete and one exists: a locale is discrete if the unique map to the terminal locale and the diagonal are both open.</p>",
        "id": 245026867,
        "sender_full_name": "Graham Manuell",
        "timestamp": 1625572105
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"386922\">Graham Manuell</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/230087-theory.3A-topos.20theory/topic/singleton.20morphism/near/245026867\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>If we are allowed to remember the order structure isn't this trivial? [proceeds to give non-trivial characterization]</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Okay, good point! With <em>all</em> of the order structure, it's certainly possible. Here's my problem: I'm constructing an object which I know <em>should</em> be such a locale. However, the construction I'm working with is only guaranteed to produce a distributive lattice; it's constructed from the images of frames/locales under an inverse image functor, and such functors aren't guaranteed to preserve completeness/infinite joins.<br>\nIf I have a distributive lattice, I can tell it's a frame because the depleted Yoneda embedding into its ideal completion will have a left adjoint. So I was wondering whether it might be possible to avoid constructing that adjoint (to show it's a locale and then a discrete locale) by instead constructing a subobject with a suitable universal property (going smaller rather than bigger).</p>",
        "id": 245028548,
        "sender_full_name": "Morgan Rogers (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1625573102
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Lol. Fair. I should have instead said that it follows easily from Stone duality.</p>\n<p>I can't immediately think of a characterisation that avoids checking it has arbitrary joins.</p>",
        "id": 245046385,
        "sender_full_name": "Graham Manuell",
        "timestamp": 1625581760
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>It's okay, I'll try constructing the adjoint/joins and see how that goes.</p>",
        "id": 245049330,
        "sender_full_name": "Morgan Rogers (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1625582935
    }
]